I SURVIVED MY FIRST CADAVER LAB! 💀⚠️ If you’re tuned into my stories (if not, you should because that’s where the real tea happens ☕️), I shared a bit of my FIRST ever experience in a cadaver lab. I asked you to vote on whether or not these un-aesthetic pics should be on my feed because the story behind them packs a punch. The reality is life isn’t always aesthetic, and med school is a massive part of mine. So I say, screw the aesthetic. I want to get REAL on this page. But anyhow, back to the story…

Gross anatomy labs that feature cadavers are a right of passage for med students. Its rarely talked about, which is odd because this can be a transformative process for many students, and some don’t make it past this point. My cohort alone lost a few students after this day. I could have been a causality of the cadaver lab, but I can proudly say I loved the experience. The irony of dissecting a human cadaver is how little you know about your cadaver and how they profoundly impact you despite that reality. 

The most startling part of the cadaver lab was the first few steps into the room. Cadavers are covered, and all you can make out is the faint outline of familiar body parts. But once they are uncovered, I felt a sense of relief and connection to this human who so heroically donated their body to science. Knowing this person wanted us to learn with them brought me an overwhelming sense of gratitude for the gift they gave us as students. Since this revelation, I have been able to take comfort in gratitude any time I become uncomfortable or sad. 

Something is humanizing about seeing the faces of our cadavers. Each time I see them, I am reminded of their humanity. I am reminded of my privilege of learning anatomy in a manner only made possible by their selfless investments in our education. I appreciate their sacrifice, and I will never forget them. 

Let me know in the comments below if you’ve ever experienced a gross anatomy lab and if you want me to continue sharing my experiences. Love you all big 💙⚕️🩺 #medschool #womeninmedicine #womeninscience #womeninSTEM

node.text: Welp, it’s official. I’m adding @licifit to the list of my top fave size-inclusive workout brands 💛 So many of us are dealing with changes in our bodies right now. The old me would’ve grabbed the baggiest, rattiest trash bag of a shirt and shorts and hid my body as best as I could. But what message does that send? That our bodies are only worthy of being adorned in nice things if we look and feel “skinny”? Nuh-uh, bestie. We deserve better than that. Put on those cute leggings and do your squats boo 🍑 #licifit #plussizefitness
